00:05:28.960 --> 00:05:32.190
I'll just go through, really
quickly, what is driving the

00:05:32.190 --> 00:05:34.090
actual display and game.

00:05:34.090 --> 00:05:36.900
So each one of these seven
monitors is being run off of a

00:05:36.900 --> 00:05:38.460
separate PC.

00:05:38.460 --> 00:05:42.010
And every single one of those is
just an instance of Chrome

00:05:42.010 --> 00:05:43.390
running in full screen.

00:05:43.390 --> 00:05:47.070
This whole thing is built
on JavaScript and web

00:05:47.070 --> 00:05:47.690
technologies.

00:05:47.690 --> 00:05:50.530
All of the communication is
handled through WebSockets

00:05:50.530 --> 00:05:53.940
just routing messages through
an instance of Node.js.

00:05:53.940 --> 00:06:01.030
So there's no native custom apps
running except for the

00:06:01.030 --> 00:06:03.990
body tracking, which is an
openFrameworks app using

00:06:03.990 --> 00:06:08.340
OpenNI and a 3D camera,
sort of like a Kinect.

00:06:08.340 --> 00:06:09.800
So that's what's driving
this thing.

00:06:09.800 --> 00:06:13.520
Each of the view ports is
basically just showing the

00:06:13.520 --> 00:06:14.560
current game state.

00:06:14.560 --> 00:06:17.690
And then we have another PC that
is not connected to any

00:06:17.690 --> 00:06:19.010
of the game displays.

00:06:19.010 --> 00:06:23.200
There's a podium that you can
see in the scene there that is

00:06:23.200 --> 00:06:25.350
running the game logic.

00:06:25.350 --> 00:06:28.100
And then game state is sent
out to all seven of the

00:06:28.100 --> 00:06:31.090
displays at about 60 hertz,
which is what we try to keep

00:06:31.090 --> 00:06:32.790
the frame rate at.

00:06:32.790 --> 00:06:37.270
So it's pretty ambitious
for something running

00:06:37.270 --> 00:06:39.060
completely in Chrome.

00:06:39.060 --> 00:06:41.620
But it's been a breeze
to work with.

00:06:41.620 --> 00:06:46.020
And the synchronization between
the displays has been

00:06:46.020 --> 00:06:48.380
not much of a problem at all.

00:06:48.380 --> 00:06:51.380
So that's basically
what's driving it.

00:06:51.380 --> 00:06:57.160
We use the three.js WebGL
library to do all of the 3D

00:06:57.160 --> 00:06:58.330
objects in the foreground.

00:06:58.330 --> 00:07:01.580
And the map plane is
actually an HTML

00:07:01.580 --> 00:07:03.350
Google Map that's live.

00:07:03.350 --> 00:07:04.730
There's no trickery going on.

00:07:04.730 --> 00:07:08.500
It's just being transformed
using 3D CSS to stay in sync

00:07:08.500 --> 00:07:10.640
with the WebGL camera.

00:07:10.640 --> 00:07:12.790
So what you're seeing is an
actual live Google Map.

00:07:12.790 --> 00:07:16.250
If I hadn't turned off the user
input, you could actually

00:07:16.250 --> 00:07:18.240
drag and zoom and pan
on the thing.

00:07:18.240 --> 00:07:21.000
Even though that would distort
the game experience, it really

00:07:21.000 --> 00:07:22.090
is there, really is running.

00:07:22.090 --> 00:07:22.894
MARTIN LINDE: [INAUDIBLE].

00:07:22.894 --> 00:07:25.900
BEN PURDY: Yeah.

00:07:25.900 --> 00:07:28.810
So that's been a fun experience
trying to marry the

00:07:28.810 --> 00:07:31.711
3D CSS with WebGL.

00:07:31.711 --> 00:07:34.960
Additionally, we had to do some
interesting trickery to

00:07:34.960 --> 00:07:36.850
get the view synchronized.

00:07:36.850 --> 00:07:40.410
So what we ended up doing is
having a dummy object in 3D

00:07:40.410 --> 00:07:44.570
space that we attached the
actual camera to, and then we

00:07:44.570 --> 00:07:47.430
just offset the rotation of that
camera depending on the

00:07:47.430 --> 00:07:48.580
view index.

00:07:48.580 --> 00:07:50.790
And then as long as each
viewport is rendering the same

00:07:50.790 --> 00:07:53.620
scene, and since they're all
synchronized over the network,

00:07:53.620 --> 00:07:55.980
the scene stays in sync.

00:07:55.980 --> 00:07:58.720
Then once you put the view
side by side, everything

00:07:58.720 --> 00:08:00.880
stitches together.

